content: [ Date Prev ][ Date Next ][ Thread Prev ][ Thread Next ][ Date Index ][ Thread Index ]        [IGSMAIL-0848] Hyougo-ken Nanbu earthquake mosaic - GPS results from GSI         Subject : [IGSMAIL-0848] Hyougo-ken Nanbu earthquake mosaic - GPS results from GSI   From : Ken Hudnut   Date : Thu, 19 Jan 1995 22:16:10 PST             ****************************************************************************** IGS Electronic Mail      Thu Jan 19 22:16:10 PST 1995      Message Number 0848 ******************************************************************************  Author: Ken Hudnut Subject: Hyougo-ken Nanbu earthquake mosaic - GPS results from GSI  Hiro Tsuji and colleagues at GSI in Japan have produced preliminary displacement results from the national continuous GPS network there.  Hiro said it's OK for me to help with distributing these early results via a mosaic site.  The new mosaic site is:   http://aladdin.gps.caltech.edu/hudnut/hyougo/hyougo.html    [Mailed From: Ken Hudnut <hudnut@seismo.gps.caltech.edu>]                       Prev by Date:  [IGSMAIL-0847] Northridge GPS - revised and additional data     Next by Date:  [IGSMAIL-0849] IAG Symposium G6     Prev by thread:  [IGSMAIL-0847] Northridge GPS - revised and additional data     Next by thread:  [IGSMAIL-0849] IAG Symposium G6     Index(es):    Date   Thread

The global data are analyzed in one or more subnetworks               and combined using the GLOBK software to compute precise orbits.               These are tightly constrained in separate GAMIT solutions:                 (1) California regional SCIGN (ambiguities fixed)                 (2) California regional BARD (ambiguities fixed)                 (3) North America CORS (ambiguities free)                 (4) Western Europe EURA (ambiguities free).                  The weekly solution reported here is generated by GLOBK,               combining all global and regional daily solutions.            (2) The site coordinate repeatabilities reported in this newsletter               are the direct results of the GLOBK adjustment. _____________________________________________________________________________ Remarks:  (1) IGS and regional data are analyzed with the GAMIT software               using a two-tier (global and regional) distributed processing               scheme. The global data are analyzed in one or more subnetworks               and combined using the GLOBK software to compute precise orbits.               These are tightly constrained in separate GAMIT solutions:                 (1) California regional SCIGN (ambiguities fixed)                 (2) California regional BARD (ambiguities fixed)                 (3) North America CORS (ambiguities free)                 (4) Western Europe EURA (ambiguities free).                  The weekly solution reported here is generated by GLOBK,               combining all global and regional daily solutions.
